SIMPLE: presentative
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Presentative
<hw>Pre*sent"a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>Having the right of presentation, or offering a
clergyman to the bishop for institution; <as>as, advowsons are
<ex>presentative</ex>, collative, or donative</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Admitting the presentation of a clergyman; <as>as, a
<ex>presentative</ex> parsonage</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Spelman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>Capable of being directly known
by, or presented to, the mind; intuitive; directly apprehensible, as
objects; capable of apprehending, as faculties.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The latter term, <qex>presentative</qex> faculty, I use . . . in
contrast and correlation to a ⟦ldquo⟧representative faculty.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Presentee</ent>⟦br⟧
